</figure>

<p>While this traditional type of persona is great for creating surface-level empathy for someone, a persona needs to feel realistic in order to serve as a useful reference to the designer. Itâ€™s easy to include too much information without giving thought to the overarching structure. Personas are a great start, but to make them a more effective tool for creating empathy, we need to include more about the Learnerâ€™s context.</p>

<h2 id="understand-the-learners-context">Understand the Learnerâ€™s context</h2>

<p>David Kelley, founder of the <a href="https://dschool.stanford.edu/">Stanford Design School</a> and <a href="https://www.ideo.com/people/david-kelley">IDEO</a> â€” both world leaders of human-centered design practicesâ€”offers <a href="https://dschool-old.stanford.edu/groups/k12/wiki/3d994/Empathy_Map.html">Empathy Maps</a> as a way to help round out the picture of what our Learners might need. These questions help shift our mindset to who our Learners are, and they provide great insight into what you can create that will help inform the learning design process. The questions are broken down into four categories:</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Says -</strong> What are some quotes your Learnerâ€™s have said?</li>
  <li><strong>Does -</strong> What actions and behaviours have you noticed?</li>
  <li><strong>Thinks -</strong> What might your Learners be thinking?</li>
  <li><strong>Feels -</strong> What emotions might your Learners be feeling?</li>
</ol>

<p>Even just spending a few minutes answering these questions will give us a clearer, more realistic picture of our Learner than we had with traditional personas. Applying these questions to our previous example might look something like this:</p>

